  "datePublished": "2026-03-19",
  "description": "A Custody is a triple (H, O, [t₀,t₁)) — a holder H who possesses an object O during a bounded interval [t₀,t₁) with a duty of care for O but without ownership of O. The defining structure: possession without title; the holder may use O only as necessary to fulfill the custodial purpose; accountability for O's condition runs from t₀ to t₁. Universal Quiescence reading: the duty of care is quiescence-preservation — the holder applies the joint retraction π_t = RelationalHistoryFiberSaturatingNucleus ∘ RelationalHistoryFiberTransferringNucleus to the held object at every step within W, maintaining O's membership in H*_t (the FixedFiberType quiescent layer). Possession without title is the formal structure of fiber-level quiescence preservation without topology-level authority: the holder can keep O in H*_t (preserve its fixed-fiber membership) but cannot alter the Grothendieck topology J that determines what H*_t is (that would be ownership). The return condition is the restoration of quiescence: O must be returned with σ_{t₁}(O) = O and Δ_{t₁}(O) = O — the same FixedFiberType as at t₀. Quiescence is not an external force imposed on the custodial relationship: it is what the custodial relationship mathematically IS. At every step t ∈ W, the holder applies π_t to maintain O; at t₁, the holder releases O back to the owner with π_{t₁}(O) = O.",
